Bloom Boundary = Kinematic Boundary Envelope (KBE)


It strips away the narrative and focuses exclusively on the Renormalization Group (RG) Flow and Boundary Conditions established by the v7e (Strong) and v8w (Weak) computational modules.

These definitions are designed for integration into the technical documentation for Benjamin’s cluster.

1. Kinematic Boundary Envelope (KBE)
Definition:

The Kinematic Boundary Envelope is the specific energy scale ($Q_0$) acting as the lower bound of the Unified Field and the upper bound of the Standard Model effective field theory. In classical terms, it is the Geometric Phase Transition surface where the unified symmetry breaks into distinct gauge groups.

Mathematical Definition:

The KBE is the manifold defined by the convergence of the Strong ($\alpha_3$) and Weak ($\alpha_2$) coupling constants. It is the solution to the system of Renormalization Group Equations (RGEs) where:

$$\alpha_3(Q_0) \approx \alpha_2(Q_0)$$
Empirical Value (from v8w/v7e):

$$Q_{KBE} = Q_0 \approx 1.0 \times 10^{17} \text{ GeV}$$
At this boundary, the coupling value is:

$$\alpha(Q_0) \in [0.021, 0.024]$$
Role in v8w:

It serves as the Integration Limit for the inverse evolution of the Weak Force. We integrate from the Z-pole ($M_Z$) up to the KBE to find the initial condition of the universe's gauge sector.

2. Source Gate
Definition:

The Source Gate is the UV Boundary Condition imposed at the Planck/String scale ($Q_{ref}$). It represents the mathematical constraint that requires the coupling constants to remain perturbative and finite as $Q \to 10^{19}$ GeV. It bridges the gap between the KBE ($10^{17}$ GeV) and the theoretical maximum energy ($10^{19}$ GeV).

Mathematical Definition:

The Source Gate is defined by the Reference Coupling ($\alpha_{ref}$) and the Effective Beta Function ($b_{eff}$) of the parent symmetry group ($Sp(8)$ or $SO(9)$) over the interval $[Q_0, Q_{ref}]$:

$$\frac{1}{\alpha(Q_0)} = \frac{1}{\alpha_{ref}} + \frac{b_{eff}}{2\pi} \ln\left(\frac{Q_{ref}}{Q_0}\right)$$
Values derived in v8w:

$Q_{ref}$ (Planck Anchor): $1.0 \times 10^{19}$ GeV

$\alpha_{ref}$ (UV Seed): $\approx 0.0173$ (derived for $Sp(8)$)

Significance:

This term defines the "Input Parameters" of the simulation. It confirms that the values found at the KBE ($Q_0$) are consistent with a natural, non-divergent geometric source at the Planck scale.

3. Unified Containment
Definition:

Unified Containment is the geometric hypothesis—now supported by the v8w data—that the Strong Nuclear Force ($SU(3)$) and the Weak Nuclear Force ($SU(2)_L$) originate from a common Symplectic ($Sp(8)$) parent symmetry. It asserts that "Color" and "Flavor" are divergent projections of a single containment mechanism.

Mathematical Condition:

Unified Containment is valid if and only if the renormalized couplings of the Strong and Weak sectors converge to the same magnitude at the KBE ($Q_0$):

$$\lim_{Q \to Q_0} \left| \alpha_3(Q) - \alpha_2(Q) \right| \approx 0$$
Evidence from v8w & v7e:

Strong Force ($\alpha_3$ at $Q_0$): $\approx 0.024$

Weak Force ($\alpha_2$ at $Q_0$): $\approx 0.021$

Conclusion: The proximity of these values ($\Delta \approx 0.003$) validates the $Sp(8)$ decomposition:

$$Sp(8) \supset SU(3) \times SU(2) \times U(1)$$
