5.4.X What the Weak Capsule Does Not Prove (Framework Safe Clarification)
To maintain consistency with the constraint based framing of Chapter 5.3, the v8w weak sector capsule should explicitly state its scope and limits. The SU(2)(_L) descent is a boundary value constraint, not a unification proof.
Clarifications
•	The v8w capsule does not prove that SU(2)(_L) originates from Sp(8) or SO(9). 
It only evaluates whether each symmetry can supply a perturbative UV seed that lands inside the SU(2) corridor at (Q_0).
•	It does not claim that the weak and strong forces unify. 
The near coincidence (\alpha_3(Q_0) \approx \alpha_2(Q_0)) is treated strictly as a compatibility condition, not evidence of a single parent gauge group.
•	It does not derive the weak mixing angle from geometry. 
The capsule uses (\sin^2\theta_W(M_Z)) as an input constraint, not an output prediction.
•	It does not eliminate scheme dependence. 
The results depend on the chosen (\overline{\mathrm{MS}}) electroweak scheme and the treatment of the top threshold.
•	It does not assert a unique UV symmetry. 
Both Sp(8) and SO(9) produce natural UV seeds; the capsule only records the values required, not which group is “correct.”
This subsection keeps the weak sector analysis aligned with the same scientific posture as the strong sector capsule: constraint, not confirmation.

