5.4.X Cross Sector Interpretation: SU(3) and SU(2)(_L) as Paired Boundary Constraints
To ensure consistency with Chapter 5.3, it helps to explicitly articulate how the strong and weak capsules relate to each other in the RG architecture.

1. Shared Boundary Scale
Both v7e (SU(3)) and v8w (SU(2)(_L)) independently identify
[ Q_0 \approx 10^{17},\mathrm{GeV} ]
as the scale at which their couplings fall into the same numerical band: [ \alpha_3(Q_0) \approx 0.024,\qquad \alpha_2(Q_0) \approx 0.021. ]
This is not treated as a unification claim — only as a shared boundary condition that both sectors satisfy under two loop RG flow.

2. Parallel Corridor Structure
Both capsules define a falsifiable window:
•	Strong corridor: 
[ \alpha_{3,0} \in [0.02175,,0.02180] ]
•	Weak corridor: 
[ \alpha_{2,0} \in [0.02112,,0.02128] ]
The overlap reinforces the interpretation of (Q_0) as a kinematic boundary, not a fitted parameter.

3. UV Bridge Consistency
Both capsules use the same analytic one loop inversion to compute the required UV seed at
[ Q_{\mathrm{ref}} = 10^{19},\mathrm{GeV}. ]
The resulting seeds:
•	Strong: (\alpha_{\mathrm{ref}} \approx 0.028)
•	Weak: (\alpha_{\mathrm{ref}} \approx 0.017)
Both lie in the perturbative regime, satisfying the same “naturalness” criterion used in Chapter 5.3.

4. Interpretation as a Paired Constraint System
Together, v7e and v8w form a two sector boundary value architecture:
•	SU(3) tests containment (steep RG slope).
•	SU(2)(_L) tests mixing (gentler RG slope).
•	Both must satisfy the same KBE boundary and the same UV anchor.
This paired structure is the foundation for extending the method to the final gauge leg, U(1)(_Y).
